WEBVTT

00:02.782 --> 00:03.523
nurse. Yeah, they were married and she had, I think 
she was about maybe two months pregnant, but this

00:04.164 --> 00:16.104
was not known. I didn't know it when he told me. I was 
shocked. I was shocked. I didn't know. I was

00:20.351 --> 00:20.992
surprised. And so was Bob Neal. And it so happens 
that old PTAC And he was one of the 16 that

00:27.335 --> 00:31.840
volunteered to stay over those extra 10 days. And 
he was killed. Oh, I see. He was killed. And it was

00:36.764 --> 00:42.630
either 16 of us for 10 days or 10 of us for 16 days. I 
forget which. At any rate, he was one of the eight

00:46.334 --> 00:57.325
pilots I told you originally about that was killed 
in combat, actually killed in the entire AVG

00:46.334 --> 00:57.325
history. Anyway, she was pregnant, and they sort 
of wanted us to look after her. Well, Red sort of

01:03.108 --> 01:10.657
took care of me in a hospital, you know, and bathed 
me when I was, you know, had come back and shot down

01:03.108 --> 01:10.657
and all that. So I had developed a close rapport 
with her. And my first reaction, of course, to Bob

01:13.801 --> 01:18.286
Neal, too, was the rapport with her. We just loved 
those nurses. And, you know, there were only two

01:19.648 --> 01:22.091
females with her. And... We said, sure. But I said, 
you know, we don't know how we're going to get home.

01:28.157 --> 01:29.239
We're going down to India. And I told him I'm going 
to try my best to pull strings in the 10th Air Force

01:29.299 --> 01:37.691
Headquarters of New Delhi to get air 
transportation back home. I don't know. I'm not

01:38.332 --> 01:40.375
even going home on a slow boat. I'm not afraid about 
submarines, but I just don't want to do that. So he

01:42.919 --> 01:44.161
said, yeah. So he told Red. And we three had come in 
then, got on an airplane, provided by the old man.

01:53.920 --> 02:00.826
got us to CNAC, Chinese National Airways 
Corporation, which was really the Chinese

01:53.920 --> 02:00.826
airline. And he was boss of that, too. So that got us 
to Calcutta. So Calcutta, we were on our own from

02:05.651 --> 02:09.555
then on. And we three stayed together all the way 
home. To make a long story short- How'd you get

02:14.159 --> 02:17.022
home? I knew General Caldwell, Colonel Caldwell 
at that time. And Colonel,

02:23.266 --> 02:38.769
I had to refer to my diary notes,

02:23.266 --> 02:38.769
he later became a four-star general in the Air 
Force and personnel. And General

02:38.789 --> 02:51.467
Nagel, who was commander, brigadier general in 
the United States Army Air Corps, 10th Air Force

02:38.789 --> 02:51.467
with headquarters in New Delhi. General Peabody, 
General Peabody. I knew all of these guys from

02:53.329 --> 02:58.196
Langley Field, the early current. They knew me. 
And of course, word got back, you know, word from

02:59.318 --> 03:03.544
the heroes. They followed very closely.

03:10.774 --> 03:17.404
I figured I'd call and work through Charlie 
Caldwell first, and I told him what the story was,

03:10.774 --> 03:17.404
and God bless him, he was just... He was 
tremendous. I think he was in the operations

03:20.126 --> 03:23.471
section. Let's

03:23.592 --> 03:29.160
correct this. General Naiden, N-A-I-D-E-N, was 
the commander of the 10th Air Force. General

03:35.389 --> 03:38.634
Peabody is the guy that sent me to Russia later on. 
But General Naiden was the commander in charge of

03:38.654 --> 03:41.558
Caldwell. So I explained to him, and I used red. 
Petak's condition is one of the reasons I said, I

03:45.329 --> 04:04.129
explained she's pregnant, and I said, quite 
frankly, I said, if you'd get her home on an

03:45.329 --> 04:04.129
airplane by ATC Air Transportation Command, 
which was under the United States Air Force,

03:45.329 --> 04:04.129
really took over Pan Am and all the airlines, you 
know what I mean. I said, really, just get her home.

04:05.831 --> 04:06.492
That's all right. Then Bob and I, if you can't get us 
on, well, okay, we'll go by ship or something.

04:11.215 --> 04:12.556
Well, he said, oh, no, no. I said, I'll tell you 
what, let me do some talking, and I'll call you

04:12.576 --> 04:16.620
back. The next day he called back and said, say, you 
come on up here to New Delhi. So we got on a train up

04:20.523 --> 04:29.891
New Delhi, and I introduced Red and Bob Neal to him, 
and they took us to dinner, and we talked at length.

04:29.991 --> 04:35.536
And this other gentleman, a great guy, I think of 
his name in a minute.

04:38.399 --> 04:41.121
Finally, they got me an audience for General 
Nadin, the commander. And I went in personally and

04:41.557 --> 04:45.502
by myself and told him the situation. He picked up 
the telephone and called General Hap Arnold's

04:45.522 --> 04:53.453
office in Washington, D.C. and explained the 
situation to him. And I think it was General Cuter

04:54.294 --> 05:05.009
or one of General Arnold's top aides who answered 
the phone and said, we'll get back with you

04:54.294 --> 05:05.009
tomorrow and give you the answer. And that 
morning, General Layton called me in the office

05:05.730 --> 05:09.775
and he handed me a wire and he said, He said, send him 
a wire. He had a wire in his hand. Give Quadrant

05:14.590 --> 05:34.359
Leader Charles R. Bond, Bob Neal, and Nurse Red 
P-Tech of the American Flying Interior Group a

05:14.590 --> 05:34.359
full accord and courtesy of the Air Transport 
Command back to the United States. And from then

05:35.942 --> 05:38.125
on, you know, no problem. So they flew you by? Yeah, 
and we got on ATC airplanes, various types.

05:45.211 --> 05:50.836
Actually, we flew in an old goonie bird from New 
Delhi clear across India to Karachi. Karachi, we

05:50.856 --> 06:06.390
flew across to Allahabad,

05:50.856 --> 06:06.390
and Allahabad to Aden, Aden to Khartoum, Khartoum 
to Tano,

06:09.172 --> 06:16.840
What do you call it, not the same name now, what is

06:09.172 --> 06:16.840
it? Gold Coast. Gold Coast. That's from the Gold 
Coast to Trans-Pertuson, an old, the only

06:18.401 --> 06:27.871
commercial version of the B-17 that ever built one 
of them. TWA. But as I mentioned, we flew from there

06:28.512 --> 06:35.879
to Natal, Natal then on this way back to Miami. Did 
you have a stunt there? Well, that's on the way

06:37.401 --> 06:38.162
over. Oh, okay. and back up to Miami.

06:49.383 --> 06:49.984
No, we did. We landed sentinel with them. That's a 
British air base at that time. And then when I got

06:56.192 --> 07:07.748
back to Miami, of course, we told Red goodbye, and 
Bob Neal and I went to New York, and Bob had ideas,

06:56.192 --> 07:07.748
and did go with Penebroke. a forerunner of Pan Am, 
eventually was taken over from Pan Am, Pan

07:08.369 --> 07:21.465
American Grace, as a pilot with an old flying boat, 
and he's Navy anyhow, and I was going to go to work

07:08.369 --> 07:21.465
for TWA. But, what happened after that? He went 
with Pan Am, I mean Pan Am, and flew with them a long

07:27.373 --> 07:34.782
time, and then finally he quit, and went to back to 
his old love, state of Washington, and he's now

07:35.099 --> 07:47.834
running a little fishing resort and been up there 
ever since on a little island in the sound right

07:35.099 --> 07:47.834
north of Seattle. And living with his wife. So he 
stayed with Pan Am for the rest of his career? No,

07:53.982 --> 07:55.564
no, he resigned from Pan Am. He resigned after 
about four or five years. Maybe six or eight years.

08:02.825 --> 08:21.212
And Red Petak is currently married to a gentleman 
who is running a,

08:02.825 --> 08:21.212
some sort of fish wholesale business in, I think 
it's Maryland, someplace in Maryland. And what

08:21.773 --> 08:24.316
did you decide to do? Well, my objective was to get a 
rate commission in the Air Force, and I didn't give

08:24.336 --> 08:30.365
up. So, I... I went with Bob Neal up and talked to 
Panagra people, and I wasn't too impressed with

08:32.997 --> 08:43.253
those people, but I still wanted commission in the 
Air Force. They wanted to go in commercial

08:43.333 --> 08:46.638
airlines.

08:47.900 --> 08:54.530
I wanted my regular commission, so I went down to 
Dallas Civilian. Had plenty of money at that time.

08:59.812 --> 09:11.570
I went down to Washington and walked into the 
munition building and kept talking to people

08:59.812 --> 09:11.570
until I got to General Hap Arnold's office and told 
him who I was. And of course, the officers, the

09:11.810 --> 09:18.761
major officers, they had certainly heard of 
Flying Tigers, and a lot of them had heard of me. I

09:19.803 --> 09:23.749
was one of the so-called heroes. And next thing I 
know, I finally got to General Cuter's office.

09:28.094 --> 09:28.875
K-U-T-E-R. He was a very good gentleman. He 
suddenly became a four-star general. Very fine.

09:33.701 --> 09:34.682
He was brilliant also. Got a half-armed 
right-hand man. And I walked into his office and I

09:37.466 --> 09:42.953
was, I was aggressive. I had one objective in mind 
and I didn't waste any time. I didn't pull any

09:46.177 --> 09:47.298
punches. And I said, I have come to see General 
Arnold, first of all. I'm sure he bought and he knew

09:51.644 --> 09:54.928
I was one. He's the one, by the way, who got us here. 
He said, well, General Arnott is going to be busy

09:59.982 --> 10:03.685
for a long time. I said, General Cuter, I know he's 
very busy, but I came here to see him. If I can't see

10:08.971 --> 10:11.313
him, then let's say so and I'll leave. He said, oh, 
no, wait a minute. Don't get mad. I said, you came

10:14.557 --> 10:16.139
here to see him, didn't you? I said, that's right. 
He said, well, don't leave until you see him. I

10:19.322 --> 10:21.544
said, well, I'm not going to wait all week. He said, 
I think we can probably get an appointment in the

10:21.564 --> 10:24.207
morning. I said, all right then, I'll wait until 
tomorrow. I hope he shook hands, and I walked down.

10:31.122 --> 10:34.667
Sure, if he called me 9 o'clock the next morning, 
I'd call him at 10, something like that. And I came

10:34.727 --> 10:47.666
down, and at the appropriate time, whenever it 
was, General Kuehler took me in General Arnold's

10:34.727 --> 10:47.666
office, and there he was sitting by his desk with 
his blouse open the way he usually does. And

10:48.747 --> 10:50.650
terrific man, terrific man. But I bet he had at 
least... six or eight generals crowding around

10:53.752 --> 10:58.937
him, standing at the desk. And it became fairly 
obvious, very obvious in no short, in a very short

10:58.957 --> 11:07.924
period of time, what all of the generals were 
doing. And... What were they doing? I'll tell you.

11:12.208 --> 11:22.257
I was, I'm going too slow for you, I know I'm 
dragging you out, but I, I took hands with the

11:12.208 --> 11:22.257
general, I said, told him where I was, and he says, 
what can I do for you? I said, General Arnold, I want

11:22.962 --> 11:25.606
a regular commission in the Air Force. I said, 
that's all I want. I said, I'll go back to China

11:26.828 --> 11:28.711
right now. I would have stayed in China, and I told 
Tex Sanders I'd stay in China if you'd give me a

11:28.731 --> 11:34.619
regular commission. I had a long talk with General 
Berg. He said he'd take Congress and give me a

11:37.443 --> 11:39.587
regular commission. I said, if anybody can give me 
a regular commission, I believe you can. I said,

11:43.152 --> 11:44.494
that's what I want. And then I'm back in the Air 
Force. I love it. He said, well... He says, Burton

11:49.743 --> 11:55.513
was right, that it will take an act of Congress, and 
I just don't see how I can do it. But tell me, young

11:55.533 --> 12:01.843
man, now tell me, what is it about the P-40 that you 
guys love and did so well? And he changed the

12:01.963 --> 12:04.568
conversation completely. And then he dominated 
me from then on, you know. And he got me started, and

12:07.252 --> 12:09.456
that's what all these journalists... They wanted 
to hear it. General Arnold was in a very bad

12:12.983 --> 12:16.448
political situation. He was being pushed by 
Congress and everybody that his superior's ego

12:16.468 --> 12:22.655
was such a fantastic airplane. He'd been shooting 
everything out of the sky, you know. He'd just

12:26.680 --> 12:30.985
eaten up American airplanes in the Philippines. 
You know, Pearl Harbor, fantastic airplane. And

12:33.508 --> 12:37.232
here, the Flying Tigers just shoot them down out of 
the sky like they're nothing. Why can't, what's

12:37.820 --> 12:40.824
the matter with you people in the Air Force? 
General Arnold was really in the spot. Here was an

12:42.687 --> 12:44.229
expert back. You know, been flying, had two, 
practically double A's. So he wants them the

12:48.195 --> 12:49.677
harshest amount. So he asked, and so I just built my 
guts right there, and I stood up and just let them

12:50.478 --> 12:57.709
have it like I'm telling you right now. And I said, 
there's not a damn thing wrong with the P-40. I

12:59.972 --> 13:01.494
said, people don't know how to fight. I said, 
there's a certain way you've got to fight it. Boy,

13:04.098 --> 13:07.383
these gentlemen stand there with their mouths 
open. And I said, it's a matter of tactics. I said,

13:10.771 --> 13:14.374
in some ways, the Japanese zero is superior to our 
airplane. But I said, in other ways, it won't match

13:14.394 --> 13:16.176
it. And then I explained the whole situation. What 
did you say? Well, the P-40 is structurally, we

13:20.640 --> 13:26.366
always build a terrific airplane. The P-40 
structurally was far superior to the zero. The

13:28.809 --> 13:36.236
zero was a tin can compared to a heavy steel, if you 
will, airplane. We could out-dive it. but we could

13:37.979 --> 13:39.301
not out-turn it. The top speed of them were about 
equal. At altitude, the jet airplane, around

13:43.306 --> 13:49.916
20,000 feet to zero, was probably superior to the 
P-40. At any altitude, it would out-turn the P-40,

13:50.096 --> 13:56.204
easily, out-climb it, out-maneuver it. You just 
could not maneuver it. But the P-40, you could put

13:58.407 --> 14:05.377
it straight down a dive and never worry about the 
tail coming off. It'd get cockeyed on you because

14:05.397 --> 14:07.480
of the propeller. Turk torsion, but it would leave 
the Zero away and he couldn't, his terminal speed

14:07.915 --> 14:20.426
was, you know, slower than if he'd fought him. 
Pretty soon he was out of gunnery range. All he had

14:21.867 --> 14:26.351
to do was dive away, go out and climb back up and use a 
tactic that Chennault told us. And that's the way

14:27.812 --> 14:30.855
we took care of the Zero. And that's what you told 
Half Iron? Yeah, and I told the story and it, you

14:32.436 --> 14:35.819
know, I summarized things. Strictly tactics. And 
I said, there's nothing in the world wrong with the

14:37.666 --> 14:40.350
Peacock. I'd go back and water it right now. And, oh 
boy, he took a death tear. Well, I made friends with

14:45.978 --> 14:48.321
the old man, obviously. But, again, he was sorry, 
and I left very, very, very sad. Oh, what did the

14:54.611 --> 14:57.194
other eight generals that were standing around 
say? Oh, they just listened. They didn't say

14:58.717 --> 14:59.678
anything? No. Oh, a few, they'd come up and answer a 
few questions. Well, you know, what's your,

15:02.382 --> 15:06.166
what's the max speed you think of the Zero? What do 
you think of the Jap pilot? Those types of

15:07.988 --> 15:12.372
questions. It'd be typical. And what'd you answer 
to the Japanese pilot question? Well, the

15:15.735 --> 15:21.080
Japanese pilot was a, in my opinion, was a 
mechanical type guy. He didn't have the, this is

15:21.120 --> 15:26.826
one that I met in combat. Why they flew their 
formation the way they did, which was absolutely

15:27.397 --> 15:33.803
asinine, I'll never know, like a play hive on 
airplanes. They stuck to 18,000 feet. Their

15:36.325 --> 15:38.167
tactics were stereotyped. We knew exactly what 
they were going to do each time they came over. They

15:40.829 --> 15:41.670
didn't bury them. The Navy pilot was far superior 
to the Army pilot, definitely. Far superior.

15:48.176 --> 15:50.898
That's the reason they bring them into 
hand-counted fine campaign. They're going to

15:50.918 --> 15:53.501
eliminate us. Had we fought zeroes all the time, 
Initially, I didn't start. I think we would have

15:58.415 --> 16:00.538
had a little bit tougher time. Sure. I still think 
we would have

16:00.858 --> 16:07.768
prevailed. The primary question was oriented to 
the P-40 versus the Zero, and that's what the old

16:07.788 --> 16:13.916
man was. In other words, they were trying to get the 
old man to buy everything like a Zero. Well, he,

16:18.482 --> 16:23.108
General Oren, wasn't for it, and his generals 
weren't for it, but they needed backup. Yeah. They

16:24.586 --> 16:28.712
wanted an expert's opinion on this, and then take 
it to Congress. And look what came out of the P-40,

16:28.912 --> 16:33.698
the P-51, one of the greatest airplanes we ever 
built. Mustang, you know? Yeah. And then the old

16:35.621 --> 16:42.430
iron-gutted jug, we called it, the P-47, you know, 
that great big thing. It had the, when you turn that

16:42.450 --> 16:47.256
thing into a power dive, you never worry about it 
coming to pieces. Run through an orange grove on a

16:47.276 --> 16:52.163
landing, you know, belly up, it never hurts you. 
And so, how long were you with General Arno? I

16:57.681 --> 17:00.745
wasn't in there long in about 45 minutes. Thank 
you. Turned around and left. Went back. Then I went

17:03.048 --> 17:03.709
home. Do you know what the date of this meeting was?

17:09.557 --> 17:10.458
That's not my diary. My diary ended when I landed in 
Miami. August the 17th. It must have been the

17:14.784 --> 17:19.751
latter part of August. I can't I don't remember, 
and I don't think I'm recording. Last of August,

17:22.380 --> 17:23.742
1942. Last of August, 1942. Okay. And subsequent 
to that, then, see, I was disappointed, and I had

17:27.328 --> 17:35.880
failed in one of my missions. I had made enough 
money to come back and buy a house for my mom and dad.

17:40.588 --> 17:42.150
I did that. How much money did you make? Oh, I came 
back with more than $10,000 in my bank. Wow. With

17:49.876 --> 17:50.817
more than $15,000. More than $15,000? Boy, that's 
a lot of money for them, isn't it? Yeah. And none of

17:57.426 --> 17:59.389
that was gambling. I didn't gamble. No, that was 
just combat pay. Combat pay and travel pay, extra

18:02.133 --> 18:10.885
pay for staying over longer, and transportation 
pay, some transportation expense pay that I

18:02.133 --> 18:10.885
didn't use. But at any rate, I achieved two of my 
objectives. I got the combat experience. Yeah. I

18:20.062 --> 18:27.532
have my mother and father put them in a home, which 
is better than they've been used to, which I felt

18:20.062 --> 18:27.532
great about. But third one, I didn't get the 
regular permission. But I still had my blood. You

18:32.940 --> 18:34.022
still had your what? I had it in my blood, the 
military. I started to work for TWA and worked for

18:36.105 --> 18:45.698
about 16 days and decided it wasn't for me and 
walked in and told Jack Person, the personnel

18:36.105 --> 18:45.698
manager, In the gravity point hangar there at 
National Air Force. Look, I'm sorry. I just, I

18:53.037 --> 18:55.640
don't have it in me. I've got to go back to the Air 
Force. And he took one look at me and says, I

18:58.583 --> 19:01.866
understand perfectly. I don't blame you a bit. He 
said, you can go right ahead. He said,

19:04.168 --> 19:09.634
furthermore, we'll pay you for the 16 days that 
you've just been taking a physical examination

19:04.168 --> 19:09.634
for us. He says, I'm proud of you. So I walked across 
to Were you flying during that time? No, I was just

19:18.187 --> 19:20.470
being, for TWA? No, I was just, 16 days, filling out 
forms and taking a physical exam. They gave me a

19:27.721 --> 19:30.265
complete physical. Okay, so then you went back 
to... At that time, I don't, I have, I'm not sure

19:30.285 --> 19:42.263
whether it was in the Pentagon, but then whether it 
was finished or not. It seemed like I went over to

19:42.530 --> 19:45.154
the Pentagon. I went back in the Air Force, or 
wherever it was. The personnel told them I'm going

19:47.938 --> 19:51.142
to go back to service. Of course, they immediately 
took me back in and put me in. As a reserve officer?

19:56.310 --> 19:58.813
As a reserve officer, second lieutenant. Second 
lieutenant? When you could have been a major?

20:01.657 --> 20:03.800
Well, legally, I had to go back that way. They 
explained to me that this is, when I went back home

20:03.820 --> 20:10.750
and told them I wanted to go back to service, this is 
the way they told me. Well, I said, Yeah, we'll take

20:11.740 --> 20:16.225
you in as a first lieutenant. We have to do this 
reserve. I think it's October the 14th, 1942.

20:22.471 --> 20:23.372
Okay. And that's when my active duty started 
again. Okay. And then in one week, they promoted me

20:26.675 --> 20:29.198
to a captain. Another week, I was promoted to a 
major. Another week, I was promoted to a

20:31.140 --> 20:33.262
lieutenant colonel. I stayed there about two or 
three months in the Pentagon. Of course, in the

20:38.605 --> 20:45.674
meantime, I'd come back to Dallas in August and got 
married to Dorn on the 14th of August, 19. Okay,

20:46.915 --> 20:58.409
before we get into this part of your career, which 
starts October 1942, there are a couple of

20:46.915 --> 20:58.409
questions, just a couple more questions I want to 
ask about the Flying Tigers. One, you landed a lot

20:59.210 --> 21:05.878
of RAF bases, Royal Air Force bases. And I was 
wondering about the relationship between the

21:06.449 --> 21:18.160
British maintenance men, the base captains, the 
fliers, and the American Flying Tigers. How'd you

21:18.480 --> 21:19.461
get along with them? Well, tremendous. Matter of 
fact, one RAF

21:21.503 --> 21:35.376
pilot, no, he was an administrative officer, he 
actually left the RAF in Rangoon And in effect,

21:36.149 --> 21:37.871
just told him to go to hell. He went up into Kunming, 
China with us and stayed with us until we

21:38.552 --> 21:43.578
disbanded. And I don't know what ever happened to 
that man, but he never, as far as I know, he never

21:43.598 --> 21:48.964
went back to the RAF. Eventually, I sort of lost 
track of him. I think his name was Davis. I don't

21:55.772 --> 21:57.053
know what happened to him. Why did he do that? He 
wasn't getting the job back? He loved us. He loved

21:59.576 --> 22:00.217
us. He wanted to stay with us. He thought we were 
without a doubt the best. He thought we were gods,

22:02.930 --> 22:05.032
superhumans. He thought we were the greatest 
outfit in the world. The RAF pilots that I met, most

22:08.857 --> 22:16.646
of them, the majority of them by far, I had a great 
respect for. I never will forget old William

22:16.686 --> 22:20.791
Commander Carey, a terrific guy. He thought the 
world and all of us. You know, we were the only ones.

22:25.897 --> 22:30.263
that were really making any progress or could, you 
know, just knock the Japs off at will. We were the

22:30.423 --> 22:34.609
only bright spot in the entire world against the 
Japanese Air Force. Against Japan. Yeah. And

22:36.571 --> 22:40.917
until, you know, Doolittle, Major Ray, and 
incidentally Doolittle folks came back. We met

